ile, there is no `BuildingUpgradeEvent` message defined - only `BuildingConstruc
tEvent`. So the code is actually reusing `BuildingConstructEvent` for both event
types. This is intentional according to the proto design, though a bit confusing
.\n\nLet me re-examine the issues more carefully:\n\n1. `consumer.go` line 97: C
omparing Redis error by string message is fragile. This is a real issue because 
Redis error messages can vary by version/locale. The go-redis library may have a
specific error type for this. Let me check if there\'s a better way.\n\n2. `even
t_dispatch_server.go` line 93: `go e.publishEvent(ctx, event)` - This starts an 
unbounded number of goroutines without recovery. If `publishEvent` panics, it wi
ll crash the program. This is a risk.\n\n3. `bus.go` line 42: `gopool.NewPool("e
ventbus-pool", 1024, gopool.NewConfig())` - The pool size is 1024. If there are 
more events, they will be queued or rejected depending on gopool behavior.\n\n4.
`idempotent.go`: Uses Redis GET/SET with "1" value. The TTL is configurable. Loo
ks fine.\n\n5. `event_consumer_server.go` line 24: `go func() { ... }()` - The g
oroutine doesn\'t have panic recovery. If `consumer.Start()` panics, it will cra
sh the server. However, `Start` itself is a long-running blocking function.\n\nL
et me check if go-redis has a specific error for BUSYGROUP.',
